145
00:12:05,400 --> 00:12:09,321
What you need is lots of, in effect, hippie communes.

146
00:12:09,321 --> 00:12:18,281
People who live together and share things and love each other and eat a reasonable amount that don't cultivate their desires and aren't selfish.

147
00:12:18,601 --> 00:12:31,721
And they, thousands, hundreds of thousands of kibbutzes or hippie communes or whatever you want to call them, they will be the sort of economic backbone, and then everything will be all right.

148
00:12:32,280 --> 00:12:35,800
This was sort of in the 60s when I was teaching that here.

149
00:12:35,800 --> 00:12:44,761
This was much more relevant because the hippies were going off to Oregon and Washington and setting up such communes in which they would share everything and all love each other.

150
00:12:44,760 --> 00:12:50,601
And it looks like an argument against Dostoevsky that, as far as I know, they've all failed.

151
00:12:50,601 --> 00:12:52,841
I don't, maybe you know more about it than I do.

152
00:12:52,841 --> 00:12:53,321
Yeah.

153
00:12:54,681 --> 00:12:55,161
What?

154
00:12:55,800 --> 00:12:57,640
Well, a cooperative is different.

155
00:12:57,640 --> 00:13:01,160
The students don't own all their goods in common, do they?

156
00:13:01,400 --> 00:13:04,280
Their clothes and their oh, okay.

157
00:13:04,280 --> 00:13:07,081
But anyway, and if it works, they're good.

158
00:13:07,081 --> 00:13:08,441
And I gather it works still.

159
00:13:08,441 --> 00:13:09,960
There are still kibbutzes in Israel.

160
00:13:09,961 --> 00:13:10,601
Anybody know?

161
00:13:10,601 --> 00:13:11,880
That's what I think.

162
00:13:12,841 --> 00:13:23,961
But it's not, let me just say, Dostoevsky, I think, would have to admit that it's not working well enough to be the general form of the economy and to solve everybody's problems.

163
00:13:23,961 --> 00:13:25,760
Now, that's not just me saying that.

164
00:13:25,920 --> 00:13:27,040
That wouldn't be interesting.

165
00:13:27,040 --> 00:13:29,440
Dostoevsky thinks it's not going to work.

166
00:13:25,081 --> 00:13:30,320
That's what's interesting.

167
00:13:30,640 --> 00:13:33,601
He's really criticizing Zosima on this one.

168
00:13:33,601 --> 00:13:42,641
Zosima thinks there should be this local communes and everybody will just love each other and help each other.

169
00:13:42,800 --> 00:13:48,241
He says it in terms of the priests on 334, those priests who don't have enough food.

170
00:13:48,241 --> 00:13:50,001
What are you going to do about that?

171
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:58,241
And he says to the priests, 12 lines from the bottom, you will penetrate their hearts with these simple tales.

172
00:13:58,241 --> 00:14:00,081
He says, tell them the Bible stories.

173
00:14:00,081 --> 00:14:03,761
Give one hour a week to it, in spite of your poverty, only a short hour.

174
00:14:03,760 --> 00:14:13,041
And you will see for yourself that our people are gracious and grateful and that we will pay you a hundredfold, mindful of the kindness of their priests and the moving words they have heard from him.

175
00:14:13,040 --> 00:14:20,641
They will, of their own accord, help him in the fields and in his house and treat him with more respect, and so will increase his worldly well-being.

176
00:14:20,640 --> 00:14:25,441
So, in a way, everybody's sort of helping, and so maybe the Amish have this too.

177
00:14:25,441 --> 00:14:29,361
I mean, it's something that it's an interesting proposal.

178
00:14:29,361 --> 00:14:36,961
And what's really surprising and interesting to me is that Dostoevsky doesn't buy it.

179
00:14:36,961 --> 00:14:51,201
You might think, if you say to Dostoevsky, if you say to Zosima, this is too idealistic, people are innately selfish, they won't want to share the fruit of their hard labor and their clothes and their books and so forth.

180
00:14:51,760 --> 00:14:53,921
Most of these communes didn't last.

181
00:14:53,921 --> 00:14:54,721
And what would that be?

182
00:14:54,800 --> 00:14:57,521
Would that be an objection to Dostoevsky?

183
00:14:57,841 --> 00:15:00,480
Well, interestingly enough, no.

184
00:15:00,800 --> 00:15:03,681
He differs from Zosima on this one.

185
00:15:03,681 --> 00:15:15,801
He thinks people are really selfish and that it basically you're not going to be able to set up this kind of shared commune-like world.

186
00:15:16,760 --> 00:15:19,880
You don't get it said clearly until 347.

187
00:15:20,201 --> 00:15:27,320
It's very important to Dostoevsky's view that ordinary human beings are Hobbesian.

188
00:15:27,321 --> 00:15:39,161
Hobbes is a philosopher who's famous for saying life is nasty, brutish, and short, and that everybody tries to get as much possessions as possible and then has to sort of guard their possessions against everybody else.

189
00:15:39,160 --> 00:15:41,400
And that's why we have government.

190
00:15:41,721 --> 00:15:44,921
So Dostoevsky has a similar view.

191
00:15:44,920 --> 00:15:51,161
He says at the bottom of 346, well, it's presented sort of backwards.

192
00:15:51,160 --> 00:15:53,241
So let me do it on 347.

193
00:15:53,241 --> 00:15:55,241
Here he's telling you what's wrong.

194
00:15:55,241 --> 00:16:03,961
This is the mysterious visitor, who we'll hear more about, who comes to talk to who Zosima knows a lot about.

195
00:16:03,961 --> 00:16:07,561
The mysterious visitor knows a lot about human nature.

196
00:16:07,561 --> 00:16:08,841
Here's what he says.

197
00:16:08,841 --> 00:16:13,000
The second sentence in the first big paragraph, 1347.

198
00:16:13,321 --> 00:16:16,040
For everyone strives to keep his individuality.

199
00:16:16,040 --> 00:16:19,961
Everyone wants to secure the greatest possible fullness of life for himself.

200
00:16:19,961 --> 00:16:27,000
But in the meantime, all his efforts result in attaining, well, not in attaining fullness of life, but self-destruction.

201
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:31,320
For instead of self-realization, he ends by arriving in complete solitude.

202
00:16:31,320 --> 00:16:34,361
All mankind in our age is split up into units.

203
00:16:34,360 --> 00:16:36,600
Man keeps apart, each in his own groove.

204
00:16:36,600 --> 00:16:38,840
Each one holds aloof, skipping a little.

205
00:16:38,921 --> 00:16:40,840
He ends up repelled by others.

206
00:16:40,840 --> 00:16:42,520
And this is the Hobbesian thing.

207
00:16:42,520 --> 00:16:48,040
He heaps up riches by himself and thinks how strong I am now and how secure.

208
00:16:48,040 --> 00:16:53,721
And in his madness, he does not understand that the more he heaps up, the more he sinks into self-destructive impotence.

209
