00:39:36,721 --> 00:39:45,800
I mean, the sacrament of confession, the way the church, both Roman and Russian, interpreted it, it's not supposed to be a public, it's not supposed to be an encounter group.

453
00:39:40,001 --> 00:39:54,041
I mean, when I first came to Berkeley, there were these encounter groups where everybody had confessed everything in front of everybody else, and everybody forgave them, and everybody felt better.

454
00:39:54,041 --> 00:40:05,881
But that's not what the church wants, and that's not even that's not what Dostoevsky wants either, because if you do it without love, it's not going to work, he thinks.

455
00:40:05,880 --> 00:40:08,680
But then what does Dostoevsky want?

456
00:40:09,001 --> 00:40:15,560
Well, he wants something like what Zosim is doing, but he wants it to have an existential basis.

457
00:40:15,561 --> 00:40:18,600
I mean, it looks like Zosima just arbitrarily does this.

458
00:40:19,800 --> 00:40:29,881
Zosima gives no explanation directly of what he is up to when he calls them in and absolves them and so forth.

459
00:40:29,880 --> 00:40:33,881
But, and now we get to the really interesting part.

460
00:40:34,201 --> 00:40:42,361
Dostoevsky is going to give you, and it'll take probably the rest of the time, an example of a real existential confession.

461
00:40:42,360 --> 00:40:44,360
And that's the mysterious visitor.

462
00:40:44,360 --> 00:40:46,841
That's what happens on 344.

463
00:40:46,840 --> 00:40:50,520
And starting on 344 is, and Zosima is telling it.

464
00:40:50,521 --> 00:40:56,440
So in a sense, Zosima is really giving you the story behind what he's doing when he calls everybody into the room.

465
00:40:56,440 --> 00:40:58,441
He knows, I think, what he's doing.

466
00:40:58,440 --> 00:41:01,081
But he tells it indirectly.

467
00:41:02,521 --> 00:41:15,441
But it's the, as he says in his letter, Dostoevsky, it's the indirect answer to the Grand Inquisitor story that you either should be confessing secretly to God, or you should be.

